ge, far more challenging encounters.<br><br>Death is &quot;permanent&quot;, unless the character is returned from the dead (not available at lower levels, generally). Being raised generally costs about a level - various methods (reincarnation, cloning, etc.) have their own similar costs.<br><br>Both D&amp;D and EQ assume you fall down &quot;bleeding to death&quot; when you go under 0hp. However, D&amp;D assumes a chance for you to stabilize, and there are feats that will allow you to automatically stop taking damage. Only certain intelligent creatures know to finish the job when you drop (or really hungry ones). Going into the purple isn't always the automatic death sentence it is here.<br><br>Now, the real kicker - a full level in D&amp;D is based on successfully navigating 13.5 equal encounters (right from their own GM sourcebooks). It may take more if you have several weaker encounters, or less if you managed to squeak through a couple of more dangerous ones. Of course, playing out a decent encounter in a tabletop variant takes a heck of alot longer than whacking a few things in a computer game.<br><br>That 13.5 target plays out in some ways similar to EQ - levels come faster at low levels, because a short battle with a kobold scouting party can be one of those equal encounters. At higher levels, you are more likely to have a bunch of lower challenge (blue) encounters, with a final challenging encounter (yellow) as part of a story arc - so levels come slower.<br><br>But what strikes me the most is the extreme disparity between those numbers - I have no idea what the &quot;equal challenge target number&quot; is per level in EQ, but I am willing to bet it a) goes up by level, and b) is in the triple digits by high levels. It is always 13.5 in D&amp;D.<br><br>Oh - for those not conversant with D&amp;D, an equal encounter is defined as a creature or situation or combination of the two with an Encounter Level of X vs. a full party of 4 level X players.<br>